 Islam. As a cross-border, migratory phenomenon, the hajj stoked officials' fears of infectious disease, Islamic revolt, and interethnic conflict, but Eileen Kane innovatively argues that it also generated new thinking within the government about the utility of the empire's Muslims and their global networks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aIslam and statezRussiaxHistory. 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimageszRussiaxHistory. 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimageszSaudi ArabiazMeccaxHistory. 4aHistory. 4aReligious Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aMecca, hajj, pilgrimage, Russia, Colonialism, Arab world.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170131340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701313423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701313/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles